   =20
      MANG VC
   =20
 =20

What I wrote above was about=C2=A0public companies=C2=A0with normal public-=
company shareholders: humans, index funds, etc. Private companies are a lit=
tle different. Private companies often have a handful of big investors, and=
 you really can figure out what they want (you can ask them!), and what the=
y want might very explicitly be something other than =E2=80=9Cmaximize the =
profits of this company.=E2=80=9D
On Thursday, Apoorv Agrawal wrote a post titled =E2=80=9CNew VC in town: =
=E2=80=98MANG=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D that got some  attention in the tech and ve=
nture capital world. Agrawal writes:

Say hello to the newest group of prolific venture capitalists in data and A=
I: Microsoft, Amazon, Alphabet, and Nvidia. Total capital raised in their 2=
023 deals was $25B+, which is ~8% of the total venture capital raised in No=
rth America.
The MANG investments are particularly concentrated in Data and AI: their de=
als raised $23B, a staggering ~30% of all deals in Data and AI. =E2=80=A6
LLM startups are some of the largest customers of compute. It turns out tha=
t cloud providers funding their customers is a great business model. The in=
vestment capital makes a round trip back to the P&L in the form of revenue =
and helps them break even on the investment faster. =E2=80=A6
While this business model of investing in your customer is not new (Illumin=
a has done this with their spinoffs and Palantir with their investments int=
o customer SPACs), it does raise a set of interesting ramifications for VCs=
.
As MANG sets prices on these rounds (e.g. OpenAI by MSFT), what does the va=
luation represent?
Does it make sense for a financial investor to participate in these rounds?
For early-stage VCs, do I want my companies to raise $ from MANG?

Basically if you=E2=80=99re a regular old venture capitalist and you invest=
 $1 billion in an artificial intelligence startup at a $10 billion valuatio=
n, you only make money if the startup eventually sells or goes public at a =
higher valuation. But if you=E2=80=99re Amazon and you invest $1 billion in=
 an AI startup at a $10 billion valuation, and as part of the deal it agree=
s to pay you $500 million a year for computing power, you can make money on=
 the commercial deal even if the investment doesn=E2=80=99t work out. You a=
re investing not only to make money on the deal, but also to increase your =
own revenue. (And you might not even be investing cash =E2=80=94 the $1 bil=
lion might be in the form of compute rather than money.) This lowers your b=
ar for investing,
  [3]
 so you will be willing to invest more money at higher valuations in AI sta=
rtups if you can also get the commercial deals. Which means that regular ol=
d VCs will either be frozen out of those deals, or will have to overpay for=
 them.
It also means that governance at these startups will be more complicated: S=
ome corporate decisions could be bad for shareholders=C2=A0as shareholders,=
 but good for the biggest shareholder=C2=A0as a commercial partner. Agrawal=
:
MANG aren=E2=80=99t purely financial investors and will have strategic dire=
ctives that may be misaligned with other purely financial investors. They m=
ay limit/block acquisition offers and financing rounds that would have been=
 advantageous from a financial standpoint but didn=E2=80=99t align with the=
ir strategic interests.

 =20
   =20
      Exxon vs. Arjuna
   =20
 =20

And then  there=E2=80=99s this:

Exxon Mobil is suing two sustainable investment firms in a bid to block the=
m from putting forward a shareholder proposal that would commit the oil com=
pany to further curb its greenhouse-gas emissions and target its customers=
=E2=80=99 emissions.
In a federal lawsuit filed in Texas on Sunday, the Houston-based oil giant =
said investment firms Arjuna Capital and Follow This became Exxon sharehold=
ers only to put forward proposals that would =E2=80=9Cdiminish the company=
=E2=80=99s existing business.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Arjuna submitted a proposal in December asking shareholders to pass resolut=
ions committing Exxon =E2=80=9Cto go beyond current plans, further accelera=
ting the pace of emission reductions in the medium-term.=E2=80=9D Follow Th=
is joined the proposal the following day, Exxon said. In a departure from E=
xxon=E2=80=99s current policy, they advise the oil company to target the em=
issions of its suppliers and customers in addition to its own.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CDefendants are asking Exxon Mobil to change its day-to-day busines=
s by altering the mix of=E2=80=94or even eliminating=E2=80=94certain of the=
 products that it sells,=E2=80=9D the oil company said in the lawsuit. Thei=
r goal, it alleged, is =E2=80=9Cto force Exxon Mobil to change the nature o=
f its ordinary business or to go out of business entirely.=E2=80=9D

Here is  Exxon=E2=80=99s complaint. There is something a little odd about g=
oing to court over this. The way this normally works is:
=09Arjuna submits a nonbinding shareholder proposal for Exxon=E2=80=99s ann=
ual meeting.=09Exxon puts the proposal in its proxy statement for the annua=
l meeting.=09Shareholders get to vote.=09The shareholders vote no: Exxon=E2=
=80=99s complaint notes that Follow This submitted very similar proposals f=
or its 2022 and 2023 annual meetings, and they got 27.1% and 10.5% of the v=
ote, respectively.=09
Even if the shareholders vote yes, Exxon doesn=E2=80=99t have to do anythin=
g about it: The proposals are nonbinding, advisory expressions of sharehold=
er desire, and the board and management are free to ignore them. Nothing in=
 the law, or in the text of the proposals, requires Exxon to do anything.=
=C2=A0=09
Even if Exxon voluntarily does what the shareholders ask, it=E2=80=99s not =
that much. Here, the proposal asks the company =E2=80=9Cto go beyond curren=
t plans, further accelerating the pace of emission reductions in the medium=
-term for its greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions across Scope 1, 2, and 3, and =
to summarize new plans, targets, and timetables.=E2=80=9D There are no hard=
 and fast requirements; the request is just =E2=80=9Cdo a bit more about gr=
eenhouse gases, and tell us what you=E2=80=99re doing.=E2=80=9D

The normal approach, for a company faced with this sort of proposal, is to =
consider it a nuisance, grumble about it, ask shareholders to vote against =
it, but not really=C2=A0worry=C2=A0about it that much. It=E2=80=99s nonbind=
ing! And the shareholders will vote no anyway! It doesn=E2=80=99t matter.
Well, the other normal approach is for the company to ask the US Securities=
 and Exchange Commission if it can omit the proposal. The  rules for proxy =
proposals require a company to include shareholder proposals in its proxy, =
and vote on them at its annual meeting, but there are lots of exceptions. I=
n particular, a company can ignore a proposal that =E2=80=9Cdeals with a ma=
tter relating to the company's ordinary business operations=E2=80=9D: The r=
ule is that the board and management run the ordinary business operations, =
and shareholders are not really allowed to meddle. A company=C2=A0can also =
omit a proposal that =E2=80=9Caddresses substantially the same subject matt=
er=E2=80=9D as a=C2=A0proposal in a previous year that didn=E2=80=99t get m=
any votes.
The company can write to the SEC saying =E2=80=9Cwe think we can omit this =
proposal=E2=80=9D and explaining why, and the SEC will either (1) write bac=
k saying =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re fine with that=E2=80=9D (this is called a =
=E2=80=9Cno-action letter=E2=80=9D) or (2) write back saying =E2=80=9Cwe do=
n=E2=80=99t agree.=E2=80=9D Exxon has written a  fair  number of these lett=
ers about other shareholder proposals, but  apparently not about this one.=
=C2=A0
Instead, it sued the shareholders. Its complaint contains some complaining =
about the SEC:

According to SEC figures, the number of proposals submitted in 2023 was 18 =
percent higher than in 2021. And the number of proposals that were voted on=
 at annual shareholder meetings rose by 40 percent during that period. Prop=
osals focused on environmental and social issues increased at an especially=
 high rate, with the number of submissions growing by 52 percent and the nu=
mber voted on by 125 percent between 2021 and 2023.
These increases during the past two years have occurred despite no change i=
n the language of the statute or the applicable SEC rules. They can be trac=
ed only to changes in SEC staff positions on the application of the shareho=
lder proposal rules.=C2=A0Such shifting staff interpretations are not bindi=
ng, however, and they do not have the force of law.

Basically Exxon=E2=80=99s complaint here is that activist shareholders subm=
it a lot of environmental proposals that other shareholders don=E2=80=99t s=
upport, Exxon considers them to be a nuisance, but=C2=A0the SEC disagrees. =
But the SEC=E2=80=99s views are not the law. So Exxon has gone to court to =
 find a friendly judge to rule that it can omit these proposals, because a =
court ruling=C2=A0is=C2=A0the law: If a court rules that Exxon can omit env=
ironmental proposals, then it (and other companies) can keep doing that for=
ever, without asking the SEC for permission. And it has sued, not the SEC, =
but the shareholder proponents, presumably figuring that will be an easier =
fight.=C2=A0
Exxon=E2=80=99s legal argument=C2=A0is that this proposal =E2=80=9Cdeals wi=
th a matter relating to the company=E2=80=99s ordinary business operations=
=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cseeks to directly interfere with management=E2=80=99=
s business judgment and micromanage ExxonMobil=E2=80=99s core business=E2=
=80=94the energy and petrochemical products and services that ExxonMobil of=
fers.=E2=80=9D (It=C2=A0also argues that this proposal is too similar to 20=
22 and 2023 proposals that didn=E2=80=99t get enough votes, so it can exclu=
de this one as repetitive.) But there is also a lot of rhetoric about how A=
rjuna and Follow This are not real shareholders:

Arjuna and Follow This are aided in their efforts by a flawed shareholder p=
roposal and proxy voting process that does not serve investors=E2=80=99 int=
erests and has become ripe for abuse by activists with minimal shares and n=
o interest in growing long-term shareholder value.
Arjuna=E2=80=99s mission is to =E2=80=9Cshrink=E2=80=9D energy companies, a=
nd its chief investment officer was found to be =E2=80=9Cmanifestly biased=
=E2=80=9D against ExxonMobil by a New York court. ... Follow This explains =
in its governing documents and customer terms that it does not aim to achie=
ve returns on behalf of its members through shares it acquires in energy co=
mpanies.=C2=A0And its website states: =E2=80=9CWe buy shares in order to wo=
rk on our mission to stop climate change, not to make a financial profit.=
=E2=80=9D ...
Arjuna and Follow This have submitted numerous shareholder proposals to ene=
rgy companies, including ExxonMobil. Although ExxonMobil=E2=80=99s sharehol=
ders have consistently rejected Arjuna=E2=80=99s and Follow This=E2=80=99s =
proposals, those proposals are expensive and time-consuming to address, and=
 they are rarely designed to promote overall shareholder value. Instead, th=
ey are frequently at odds with the interests of investors who are seeking t=
o obtain returns for their pensions, 401(k) plans, and other savings and re=
tirement investments.

This is not a legal argument; the legal argument is the thing about the ord=
inary course of business. It is a philosophical argument: Real shareholders=
=C2=A0care only about shareholder value and long-term returns for their ret=
irement savings; shareholders who want anything else are abusing the system=
.

 =20
   =20
      Capital Zero
   =20
 =20

Thebig meta-story in recent financial history is that interest rates were z=
ero for a long time, and people got used to that, and then they suddenly we=
nt up, and there was a painful period of adjustment as everyone=E2=80=99s e=
xpectations were confounded. This arguably explains the 2023=20
regional banking troubles, and tech startups, and crypto, and=20
maybe ESG, but also lots of minor adjustments like=20
private credit hurdle rates. Also here is a Wall Street Journal  story abou=
t Capital One Financial:

When the Federal Reserve started raising interest rates in 2022, many custo=
mers of the McLean, Va., bank assumed their rates would go up. Instead, Cap=
ital One is paying them far below the 4.35% it advertises on its main savin=
gs account.
The issue dates back to a little-noticed change Capital One made in the era=
 of low rates. In 2019, the lender introduced a new savings account called =
360 Performance Savings. Existing customers were kept in older accounts tha=
t had a similar name, 360 Savings, which the bank previously advertised as =
having =E2=80=9Ca great rate=E2=80=9D but has since closed to new customers=
. When the Fed started its rate increases, Capital One only raised rates on=
 360 Performance Savings accounts.=C2=A0

See, see, see, 360 Performance Savings pays 4.35%, but 360 Savings does not=
. If you want performance from your savings, you need performance savings, =
otherwise you just get savings. Back when rates everywhere were basically z=
ero, this difference did not matter and nobody=C2=A0noticed it, which is ho=
w some people were in the bad savings account while others were in the good=
 one. Now that matters.

 =20
   =20
      Quants
   =20
 =20

Many stories about retail stock investors are   essentially entertainment s=
tories. People enjoy buying some stock because it is like watching a televi=
sion show, or joining a social-media community, or role-playing Gordon Gekk=
o. They are not maximizing risk-adjusted returns; they are optimizing on mu=
ltiple dimensions; they want some returns but also some fun. WallStreetBets=
 Reddit posters love posting their losses, because a big loss is bad financ=
ially but makes you more of a player in the Reddit community. The game is m=
ore fun if it is played in a swashbuckling way, though that can also make i=
t less lucrative.
In the world of professional investing, quantitative investing tends to be =
about=C2=A0reducing=C2=A0swashbuckling tendencies: Instead of trusting your=
 gut on a stock pick, you use carefully tested signals to pick stocks witho=
ut emotion and try to minimize your factor exposures so that you are taking=
  only the risks you are being=C2=A0paid to take. In the world of retail da=
y traders, that just isn=E2=80=99t very much fun is it? Here=E2=80=99s a Wa=
ll Street Journal story titled =E2=80=9CMeet the Investors Trying Quantitat=
ive Trading at Home,=E2=80=9D and they have some fun:=C2=A0

Daniel Hutchens, 40, is a former Microsoft cybersecurity engineer who codes=
 his own trading strategies on platforms such as Interactive Brokers. But h=
e recently improved the performance of one of them, he said, by replacing a=
 Nasdaq-100 index-tracking ETF with others holding semiconductor stocks=E2=
=80=94an idea that developed on Discord after he shared his strategy there.
=E2=80=9CI could be like, =E2=80=98Hey, here=E2=80=99s this harebrained, ha=
lf-baked idea, play with it if you want,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D said Hutchens ab=
out posting on the site. =E2=80=9CAnd then next thing you know, 45 iteratio=
ns later, it=E2=80=99s actually something viable or something horrendous. Y=
ou don=E2=80=99t know what you=E2=80=99re going to get. And it=E2=80=99s ne=
at.=E2=80=9D

If it was always something viable, it wouldn=E2=80=99t be neat. The chance =
of something horrendous is what makes it exciting.

