odd joy that its retail shareholders get out of owning the stock. And that=
=E2=80=99s what they want, so the company gives it to them.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These are the most prominent examples that we=
=E2=80=99ve discussed around here. But the general form of this is:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The company has shareholders,</li>=09<=
li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Those shareholders (or a lot of them anywa=
y) have some identifiable (or at least plausible) preferences other than ma=
ximizing=C2=A0the stock price, and</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;"=
>The company=E2=80=99s executives should (or could, or might want to, or mi=
ght be incentivized to) optimize those preferences, and sometimes prioritiz=
e them ahead of maximizing profits or the stock price.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I should say that this idea is controversial, =
both in its specific forms (environmental, social and governance investing =
is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34082724.257405=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDEtMTcvbW=
