<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">MANG VC</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What I wrote above was about=C2=A0<em>public c=
ompanies=C2=A0</em>with normal public-company shareholders: humans, index f=
unds, etc. Private companies are a little different. Private companies ofte=
n have a handful of big investors, and you really can figure out what they =
want (you can ask them!), and what they want might very explicitly be somet=
hing other than =E2=80=9Cmaximize the profits of this company.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On Thursday, Apoorv Agrawal wrote a post title=
d =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3408272=
4.257405/aHR0cHM6Ly9hcG9vcnYwMy5jb20vcC9tYW5n/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf323=
2cbd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;">New VC in town: =E2=80=98MANG=E2=80=99</a>=E2=80=9D that got =
some <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34082724.2574=
05/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9iZ3VybGV5L3N0YXR1cy8xNzQ4MDA2MTM1OTEzNzQ2NzA1=
P3M9MjA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7d589375" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> attention</a> in the te=
ch and venture capital world. Agrawal writes:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Say hello to the newest group of prolific vent=
ure capitalists in data and AI: Microsoft, Amazon, Alphabet, and Nvidia. To=
tal capital raised in their 2023 deals was $25B+, which is ~8% of the total=
 venture capital raised in North America.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The MANG investments are particularly concentr=
ated in Data and AI: their deals raised $23B, a staggering ~30% of all deal=
s in Data and AI. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">LLM startups are some of the largest customers=
 of compute. It turns out that cloud providers funding their customers is a=
 great business model. The investment capital makes a round trip back to th=
e P&amp;L in the form of revenue and helps them break even on the investmen=
t faster. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While this business model of investing in your=
 customer is not new (Illumina has done this with their spinoffs and Palant=
ir with their investments into customer SPACs), it does raise a set of inte=
resting ramifications for VCs.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As MANG sets prices on these rounds (e.g. Open=
AI by MSFT), what does the valuation represent?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Does it make sense for a financial investor to=
 participate in these rounds?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For early-stage VCs, do I want my companies to=
 raise $ from MANG?</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Basically if you=E2=80=99re a regular old vent=
ure capitalist and you invest $1 billion in an artificial intelligence star=
tup at a $10 billion valuation, you only make money if the startup eventual=
ly sells or goes public at a higher valuation. But if you=E2=80=99re Amazon=
 and you invest $1 billion in an AI startup at a $10 billion valuation, and=
 as part of the deal it agrees to pay you $500 million a year for computing=
 power, you can make money on the commercial deal even if the investment do=
esn=E2=80=99t work out. You are investing not only to make money on the dea=
l, but also to increase your own revenue. (And you might not even be invest=
ing cash =E2=80=94 the $1 billion might be in the form of compute rather th=
an money.) This lowers your bar for investing,<a class=3D"footnote-index" h=
ref=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: i=
nline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a> so you will be willing to invest more money at higher valuations in AI=
 startups if you can also get the commercial deals. Which means that regula=
r old VCs will either be frozen out of those deals, or will have to overpay=
 for them.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It also means that governance at these startup=
s will be more complicated: Some corporate decisions could be bad for share=
holders=C2=A0<em>as shareholders</em>, but good for the biggest shareholder=
=C2=A0<em>as a commercial partner</em>. Agrawal:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">MANG aren=E2=80=99t purely financi=
al investors and will have strategic directives that may be misaligned with=
 other purely financial investors. They may limit/block acquisition offers =
and financing rounds that would have been advantageous from a financial sta=
ndpoint but didn=E2=80=99t align with their strategic interests.</p></block=
quote>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Exxon vs. Arjuna</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/34082724.257405/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9idXNpbmVzcy9=
lbmVyZ3ktb2lsL2V4eG9uLXN1ZXMtdHdvLWVzZy1pbnZlc3RvcnMtMjA1N2U2OTY_bW9kPWl0cF=
93c2o/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb79e5fa4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> there=E2=80=99s this</a=
>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Exxon Mobil is suing two sustainable investmen=
t firms in a bid to block them from putting forward a shareholder proposal =
that would commit the oil company to further curb its greenhouse-gas emissi=
ons and target its customers=E2=80=99 emissions.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a federal lawsuit filed in Texas on Sunday,=
 the Houston-based oil giant said investment firms Arjuna Capital and Follo=
w This became Exxon shareholders only to put forward proposals that would =
=E2=80=9Cdiminish the company=E2=80=99s existing business.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Arjuna submitted a proposal in December asking=
 shareholders to pass resolutions committing Exxon =E2=80=9Cto go beyond cu=
rrent plans, further accelerating the pace of emission reductions in the me=
dium-term.=E2=80=9D Follow This joined the proposal the following day, Exxo=
n said. In a departure from Exxon=E2=80=99s current policy, they advise the=
 oil company to target the emissions of its suppliers and customers in addi=
tion to its own.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CDefendants are asking Exxon Mobil to =
change its day-to-day business by altering the mix of=E2=80=94or even elimi=
nating=E2=80=94certain of the products that it sells,=E2=80=9D the oil comp=
any said in the lawsuit. Their goal, it alleged, is =E2=80=9Cto force Exxon=
 Mobil to change the nature of its ordinary business or to go out of busine=
ss entirely.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/34082724.257405/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVu=
dHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JQRFdsaFJIQXh0OC92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
Be453816c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;"> Exxon=E2=80=99s complaint</a>. There is something a lit=
tle odd about going to court over this. The way this normally works is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Arjuna submits a nonbinding sharehold=
er proposal for Exxon=E2=80=99s annual meeting.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-=
bottom: 5px;">Exxon puts the proposal in its proxy statement for the annual=
 meeting.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Shareholders get to vote=
.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The shareholders vote no: Exxon=
=E2=80=99s complaint notes that Follow This submitted very similar proposal=
s for its 2022 and 2023 annual meetings, and they got 27.1% and 10.5% of th=
e vote, respectively.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">
<em>Even if the shareholders vote yes</em>, Exxon doesn=E2=80=99t have to d=
o anything about it: The proposals are nonbinding, advisory expressions of =
shareholder desire, and the board and management are free to ignore them. N=
othing in the law, or in the text of the proposals, requires Exxon to do an=
ything.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">
<em>Even if Exxon voluntarily does what the shareholders ask</em>, it=E2=80=
=99s not that much. Here, the proposal asks the company =E2=80=9Cto go beyo=
nd current plans, further accelerating the pace of emission reductions in t=
he medium-term for its greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions across Scope 1, 2, an=
d 3, and to summarize new plans, targets, and timetables.=E2=80=9D There ar=
e no hard and fast requirements; the request is just =E2=80=9Cdo a bit more=
 about greenhouse gases, and tell us what you=E2=80=99re doing.=E2=80=9D</l=
i>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The normal approach, for a company faced with =
this sort of proposal, is to consider it a nuisance, grumble about it, ask =
shareholders to vote against it, but not really=C2=A0<em>worry=C2=A0</em>ab=
out it that much. It=E2=80=99s nonbinding! And the shareholders will vote n=
o anyway! It doesn=E2=80=99t matter.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well, the other normal approach is for the com=
pany to ask the US Securities and Exchange Commission if it can omit the pr=
oposal. The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/340827=
24.257405/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L2Nmci90ZXh0LzE3LzI0MC4xNGEtO=
A/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBcbf7934a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> rules for proxy proposals</a>=
 require a company to include shareholder proposals in its proxy, and vote =
on them at its annual meeting, but there are lots of exceptions. In particu=
lar, a company can ignore a proposal that =E2=80=9Cdeals with a matter rela=
ting to the company's ordinary business operations=E2=80=9D: The rule is th=
at the board and management run the ordinary business operations, and share=
holders are not really allowed to meddle. A company=C2=A0can also omit a pr=
oposal that =E2=80=9Caddresses substantially the same subject matter=E2=80=
=9D as a=C2=A0proposal in a previous year that didn=E2=80=99t get many vote=
s.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The company can write to the SEC saying =E2=80=
=9Cwe think we can omit this proposal=E2=80=9D and explaining why, and the =
SEC will either (1) write back saying =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re fine with that=
=E2=80=9D (this is called a =E2=80=9Cno-action letter=E2=80=9D) or (2) writ=
e back saying =E2=80=9Cwe don=E2=80=99t agree.=E2=80=9D Exxon has written a=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34082724.257405/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9jb3JwZmluLzIwMjEtMjAyMi1zaGFyZWhvbGRlci1wcm9wb3Nh=
bHMtbm8tYWN0aW9uPw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9e194723" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> fair</a> <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34082724.257405/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9jb3JwZmluLzIwMjItMjAyMy1zaGFyZWhvbGRlci1wcm9wb3NhbHMt=
bm8tYWN0aW9uPw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB34bfc5f0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> number</a> of th=
ese letters about other shareholder proposals, but <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34082724.257405/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi=
9jb3JwZmluLzIwMjMtMjAyNC1zaGFyZWhvbGRlci1wcm9wb3NhbHMtbm8tYWN0aW9uPw/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cB8fffe5a5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> apparently not</a> about this one.=C2=
=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Instead, it sued the shareholders. Its complai=
nt contains some complaining about the SEC:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">According to SEC figures, the number of propos=
als submitted in 2023 was 18 percent higher than in 2021. And the number of=
 proposals that were voted on at annual shareholder meetings rose by 40 per=
cent during that period. Proposals focused on environmental and social issu=
es increased at an especially high rate, with the number of submissions gro=
wing by 52 percent and the number voted on by 125 percent between 2021 and =
2023.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These increases during the past two years have=
 occurred despite no change in the language of the statute or the applicabl=
e SEC rules. They can be traced only to changes in SEC staff positions on t=
he application of the shareholder proposal rules.=C2=A0Such shifting staff =
interpretations are not binding, however, and they do not have the force of=
 law.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Basically Exxon=E2=80=99s complaint here is th=
at activist shareholders submit a lot of environmental proposals that other=
 shareholders don=E2=80=99t support, Exxon considers them to be a nuisance,=
 but=C2=A0<em>the SEC disagrees</em>. But the SEC=E2=80=99s views are not t=
he law. So Exxon has gone to court to <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/34082724.257405/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucmV1dGVycy5jb20vbGVnYWw=
vZXh4b24tZmlsZXMtbGF3c3VpdC1hZ2FpbnN0LWludmVzdG9ycy1jbGltYXRlLXByb3Bvc2FsLT=
IwMjQtMDEtMjEv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc582bb52" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> find a friendly =
judge</a> to rule that it can omit these proposals, because a court ruling=
=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>the law: If a court rules that Exxon can omit enviro=
nmental proposals, then it (and other companies) can keep doing that foreve=
r, without asking the SEC for permission. And it has sued, not the SEC, but=
 the shareholder proponents, presumably figuring that will be an easier fig=
ht.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Exxon=E2=80=99s legal argument<em>=C2=A0</em>i=
s that this proposal =E2=80=9Cdeals with a matter relating to the company=
=E2=80=99s ordinary business operations=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cseeks to dire=
ctly interfere with management=E2=80=99s business judgment and micromanage =
ExxonMobil=E2=80=99s core business=E2=80=94the energy and petrochemical pro=
ducts and services that ExxonMobil offers.=E2=80=9D (It=C2=A0also argues th=
at this proposal is too similar to 2022 and 2023 proposals that didn=E2=80=
=99t get enough votes, so it can exclude this one as repetitive.) But there=
 is also a lot of rhetoric about how Arjuna and Follow This are not real sh=
areholders:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Arjuna and Follow This are aided in their effo=
rts by a flawed shareholder proposal and proxy voting process that does not=
 serve investors=E2=80=99 interests and has become ripe for abuse by activi=
sts with minimal shares and no interest in growing long-term shareholder va=
lue.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Arjuna=E2=80=99s mission is to =E2=80=9Cshrink=
=E2=80=9D energy companies, and its chief investment officer was found to b=
e =E2=80=9Cmanifestly biased=E2=80=9D against ExxonMobil by a New York cour=
t. ... Follow This explains in its governing documents and customer terms t=
hat it does not aim to achieve returns on behalf of its members through sha=
res it acquires in energy companies.=C2=A0And its website states: =E2=80=9C=
We buy shares in order to work on our mission to stop climate change, not t=
o make a financial profit.=E2=80=9D ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Arjuna and Follow This have submitted numerous=
 shareholder proposals to energy companies, including ExxonMobil. Although =
ExxonMobil=E2=80=99s shareholders have consistently rejected Arjuna=E2=80=
=99s and Follow This=E2=80=99s proposals, those proposals are expensive and=
 time-consuming to address, and they are rarely designed to promote overall=
 shareholder value. Instead, they are frequently at odds with the interests=
 of investors who are seeking to obtain returns for their pensions, 401(k) =
plans, and other savings and retirement investments.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is not a legal argument; the legal argume=
nt is the thing about the ordinary course of business. It is a philosophica=
l argument: <em>Real</em> shareholders=C2=A0care only about shareholder val=
ue and long-term returns for their retirement savings; shareholders who wan=
t anything else are abusing the system.</p>
